       President Johnson:
       We face more cost,

107
00:05:45,845 --> 00:05:50,649
    more loss and more agony.

108
00:05:53,386 --> 00:05:55,454
          Steve Hopper:
       In December of '66,

109
00:05:55,521 --> 00:05:59,324
   we had finished all of our
   training and declared to be

110
00:05:59,392 --> 00:06:02,427
     ready to go to Vietnam,
  but all of us got to go home

111
00:06:02,495 --> 00:06:07,632
  for Christmas and home leave,
  so to speak, before we left.

112
00:06:11,771 --> 00:06:14,573
    Bill Reynolds: I remember
      coming home and just

113
00:06:14,640 --> 00:06:18,043
     seeing my mom and dad,
     my brother and sister,

114
00:06:18,111 --> 00:06:22,581
             and my
      girlfriend was there.

115
00:06:22,882 --> 00:06:25,117
       And you know my mom
      was upset, you know,

116
00:06:25,184 --> 00:06:28,820
         she was worried
         about Vietnam.

117
00:06:28,888 --> 00:06:32,057
         And I was just
    upset to be leaving home.

118
00:06:32,125 --> 00:06:36,495
         I wasn't really
       in fear of my life.

119
00:06:36,562 --> 00:06:38,730
   Terry McBride: I had a lot
   of my cousins and aunts and

120
00:06:38,798 --> 00:06:41,133
        uncles that were
      saying goodbye to me.

121
00:06:41,200 --> 00:06:45,537
   And I could see by the look
  in some of their eyes that it

122
00:06:45,605 --> 00:06:48,974
   was probably the last time
   they were going to see me.

123
00:06:49,041 --> 00:06:51,510
      The whole thing sent
      a shiver up my back.

124
00:06:51,577 --> 00:06:53,278
        And I just said,

125
00:06:53,346 --> 00:06:56,548
    "Wait a second, how about
     everybody just tell me,

126
00:06:56,616 --> 00:06:58,750
      I'll see you later."

127
00:06:58,785 --> 00:07:02,020
       And I've always had
     a problem with goodbye.

128
00:07:02,088 --> 00:07:05,290
          To me it just
        sounds too final.

129
00:07:07,960 --> 00:07:11,730
       Steve Hopper: So I
    flew back to Illinois and

130
00:07:11,798 --> 00:07:16,968
   first thing I did was went
  out and bought an engagement

131
00:07:17,036 --> 00:07:23,508
      ring because I wanted
   the girl that I was dating,

132
00:07:27,146 --> 00:07:33,552
      I guess to give me a
  real purpose for coming home.

133
00:07:34,554 --> 00:07:37,522
           <i> Narrator:</i>
     <i> On January 10th, 1967,</i>

134
00:07:37,590 --> 00:07:40,124
         <i> the 160 men of</i>
     <i> Charlie Company depart</i>

135
00:07:40,226 --> 00:07:42,627
         <i> San Francisco</i>
       <i> Harbor on board a</i>

136
00:07:42,695 --> 00:07:47,132
  <i> World War II era transport.</i>

137
00:07:47,200 --> 00:07:49,534
   <i> In three weeks time, they</i>
   <i> will land in South Vietnam</i>

138
00:07:49,602 --> 00:07:55,340
        <i> and begin their</i>
     <i> year long combat tour.</i>

139
00:07:59,145 --> 00:08:01,847
           John Young:
       I wanted to serve.

140
00:08:01,914 --> 00:08:07,118
   My father and all my uncles
 were World War II veterans and

141
00:08:07,186 --> 00:08:13,425
    it seemed to me that this
was simply my generation's turn.

142
00:08:14,827 --> 00:08:17,596
    Jack Benedick: We figured
 within a year the war would be

143
00:08:17,663 --> 00:08:20,315
            over with
       once we got there.

144
00:08:20,399 --> 00:08:24,870
  That sounds a little, maybe,
   unrealistic to some people.

145
00:08:24,937 --> 00:08:30,642
   But the training we had at
   Fort Riley instilled in our

146
00:08:30,710 --> 00:08:34,646
     unit this will to win,
      that we were going to

147
00:08:34,714 --> 00:08:39,284
        take care of this
    war and get it over with.

148
00:08:41,153 --> 00:08:48,059
   Richard Rubio: It was like
  the old World War II movies.

149
00:08:48,361 --> 00:08:54,132
       Passing underneath
     the Golden Gate Bridge.

150
00:08:54,333 --> 00:08:58,703
     We had a lot of pride.

151
00:08:59,338 --> 00:09:01,973
     Reporter: Nicknamed the
    "old reliables" for their

152
00:09:02,074 --> 00:09:04,743
    distinguished performance
        in World War II,

153
00:09:04,810 --> 00:09:07,646
     the crack 9th Division
   will add an important plus

154
00:09:07,713 --> 00:09:10,916
        to US operations,
 and raise total troop strength

155
00:09:10,983 --> 00:09:15,854
          in Vietnam to
     another all time high.

156
00:09:24,096 --> 00:09:26,731
     Gary Maibach: The next
   morning when we woke up it

157
00:09:26,799 --> 00:09:28,867
       wasn't what I would
      call rough sea but it

158
00:09:28,935 --> 00:09:31,036
        was rough enough.

159
00:09:31,103 --> 00:09:35,273
  Bill Reynolds: That ship was
  not like cruise ships today.

160
